### 2.1 - Systems of Linear Equations

> Level: Bac+1 ?

- Central role in [[Topics/Mathematics/Linear Algebra|Linear Algebra]]
- Many problems can be formulated as **systems of linear equations**
- Examples
	- Production of n objects with r required resources
		- => find optimal production plan
		- unknowns $x_1,...,x_n$ : unit of each product to produce
		- $b_i$ unit of resource $R_i$ available
- 3 types of solutions
	- no solution
	- unique solution
	- infinitely many solutions
- Geometric interpretation
	- plan, line, point, no solution

### 2.3 - Solving SLEs (p. 27 -> p. 35)

- **Definitions**
	- Particular (aka. special) & general solution
		- eg. : if the system has 2 equations are 4 unknowns => expect infinitely many solutions
		- **to find a general solution** (3 steps)
			- Find a *particular solution* of $Ax=b$ (-> inhomogeneous linear systems)
			- Find all solutions to $Ax=0$ (-> homogeneous linear systems)
			- Combine the solutions from step 1 and 2 to the general solution
				- Adding 0 to our special solution does not change the special solution...
		- ==Neither the general nor the particular solution is unique.==
		- general solution captures the set of all possible solutions **?**
		- a constructive algorithm exists : Gaussian Elimination, to express the SLE in a convenient form (REF?/RREF?), to apply these 3 steps on.
	- **==Pivot==** (or leading coefficient) -> the first nonzero number from the left
	- **Staircase structure** : in row-echelon form (pivots are always 1)
	- **==Augmented matrix==** -> add the numbers at the right of the "=" : $[A|b]$
		- why ?
	- **==Row-Echelon form==** (**`REF`**) : convenient augmented form matrix
		- -> shape resulting from a **Gaussian elimination**
		- ==not unique, contrary to the== `RREF`
	- **Basic (leading) & Free variables**
		- **free** : $x_i$ where column $i$ has no pivot ?
			- if the number of variables exceeds the number of equations, then there is always **one free variable** => ?
				- Example : if 3 unknowns but only 2 constraints => 1 free variable
		- **basic** : if it correspond to a pivot column
		- to find basic/free variables : put the augmented matrix to REF
	- **==Reduced Row Echelon form==** (**`RREF`**) (= row canonical form)
		- -> Row Echelon form + pivots are all 1 **and** : ==0 every cells in the column which have a pivot ... !==
			- -> useful in section **2.3.3** (the Minus-1 trick)
			- Applications ?
				- [ ] in iterative methods ?
				- [ ] ...?
		- sometimes it can even reach the shape of an identity matrix => **when?**
		- If **==[[___INBOX___/__à trier/Gaussian elimination|Gaussian Elimination]]==** which will put the augmented matrix in **`RREF`** => it's called **Gauss-Jordan elimination**
			- Gaussian Elimination ==does not work on singular matrices== (they lead to division by zero)
			- Two steps : **Forward elimination** & **Back substitution**

https://adamdhalla.medium.com/linear-algebra-4-reduced-row-echelon-form-for-solving-ax-0-74f64b4f37ce
- An other method of find nullspace solutions -> with block matrices

##### 2.3.2 - Elementary transformations
- that keep the solution set the same, but transform the SLE in simpler form
	- Exchange (=interchange) of rows
	- Multiplication by a constant (not 0)
	- additions of 2 rows

##### 2.3.3 - The Minus-1 trick
- From RREF, add -1 pivot where missing => to have a n x n matrix at the end with diagonal values = **-/+1** => then easily read solutions for $Ax=0$... **(?)**
- Application : *Calculating the inverse*
	- Use $I$ => in an augmented matrix $[A|I]\rightarrow[I|A^{-1}]$
	- ...
- *Further explanation of why it works* -> https://math.stackexchange.com/a/3972375

##### 2.3.4 - Algorithms for solving SLE
- calculating the inverse $A^{-1}$ -> **Example 2.9**
	- by **Gaussian Elimination**
- **Moore-Penrose pseudo-inverse** $(A^TA^{-1})^{-1}A^{T}$
	- -> see [[Topics/Mathematics/Moore-Penrose inverse|Moore-Penrose inverse]]
	- also correspond to ==the minimal norm least-square solution== => ?
- **==Gaussian Elimination==** -> algorithm which performs a finite sequence of `elementary transformations` to bring a SLE into `(reduced) row-echelon form` then by back substitution => solve the SLE
	- useful when computing [[Topics/Mathematics/Determinant (Matrix)|Determinant (Matrix)]] -> ***section 4.1***
	- to check if a set of vectors is **linearly independent** -> **section 2.5**
	- computing the inverse of matrix -> **section 2.2.2**
	- computing the rank of matrix -> **section 2.6.2**
	- determining a basis of a vector space -> **section 2.6.1**
		- by using row-echelon form
- When many linear equations -> scales cubically in the number of equations ...
	- => but it can be solved indirectly :
		- -> see [[___INBOX___/__à trier/Iterative methods (SLE)|Iterative methods (SLE)]]
		- by stationary **(?)**
			- Richardson method, Jacobi method, Gauss-Seidel method, Successive over-relaxation (SOR) method (a variant of Gauss-Seidel), SSOR, ...
		- by **Krylov subspace** methods -> search for an approximate solution from a Krylov subspace
			- https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sous-espace_de_Krylov
			- conjugate gradients, biconjugate gradients
			- Generalized minimal residual method (GMRES, **1986**)
				- https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/GMRES

=> https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iterative_method#Linear_systems

###### Benefits of RREF
- See : https://www.reddit.com/r/learnmath/comments/29d2ms/linear_algebra_whats_the_benefit_of_reduced_row/
- get the ==inverse of a matrix== by augmenting with identity matrix and finding the ==RREF== => **`done in Colab`**
- [ ] Use of the Minus-1 trick to find general solutions ("null space" solutions)
- **easily see the solutions**
	- RREF takes longer to calculate but the values can be read straight off, whereas REF requires (more?) back substitution
- most useful for identifying your solution (null space basis) **when free variables are involved**
	- easily see the **nullspace** of a matrix -> the Xs where $Ax$ is 0 (and a scalar multiplication)
	- more easily than REF
- gives you a unique basis for the **row space** ??
	- ex: to compare if two matrices are **row equivalent** (a matrix can changed to an other, by elementary row operations)
	- ex: to check if two lists of vectors span the same subspace

### 2.4 - Vector spaces
- **2.4.1** - Groups
	- Abelian = commutative
	- Group if
		- Closure under operation
		- Associativity
		- Neutral element
		- Inverse element
	- GL(n, R) : general linear group (matrices $n\times n$) -> but not Abelian
- **2.4.2** - Vector spaces
	- inner/outer operations ...
	- convention : x, b : *column vector*
	- $ab^\intercal$ -> outer product, $a^\intercal b$ -> inner(scalar/dot) product
- **2.4.3** - Vector subspaces
	- ==Every subspace $U\subseteq(\mathbb{R}^n,+,.)$ is the solution space of homogeneous system of linear equations $Ax=0$ for $x\in \mathbb{R}^n$==

### 2.6 - Basis & Rank
- **2.6.1** - **==Generating set==**
	- Generating set : a set (A) of vectors that "span" the vector (sub)space V => $V=span(A)$
	- the smallest generating set -> **==basis==** if no smaller set of vectors
	- **`Every linearly independent generating set of V is minimal and is called a basis of V`**
	- **==Basis==**
		- `maximal linearly independent set of vectors in V`
		- ==every linear combination is **unique**== -> ?
	- A set of vectors can be linearly independent without being a basis

### 2.7 - Linear Mappings
- `Linear mappings can be represented as matrices`
- Mapping can be : Injective / Surjective / Bijective
- Homomorphism : 

#### 2.7.2 - Basis Change

```ad-info
title:
**Matrix similarity**, what is it ? (*Definition 2.22*) #card

- Two matrices $A$ and $\tilde{A}$ are similar if there exists a regular (=invertible) matrix $S\in\mathbb{R}^{n \times n}$ such that $\tilde{A}=S^{-1}AS$
- *Remark* : similar matrices are always equivalent. However, equivalent matrices are not necessarily similar.
- They possess the same determinant, trace and also same eigenvalues
- useful for the definition of "diagonalizable" matrices

---
```
